{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> φάρμᾰκον</b> <br /> [see. entry near the end], τό, <b>drug,</b> whether healing or noxious: in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] the sense is frequently determined by an epithet, φάρμακα, πολλὰ μὲν ἐσθλὰ.., πολλὰ δὲ λυγρά [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.230; τόδε φ. ἐσθλόν 10.287, compare 292; φ. ἤπια, ὀδυνήφατα (see. below 2); κακὰ φ. [prev. work] 213; φ. λυγρά [prev. work] 236 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φ. οὐλόμενον[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 394; ἀνδροφόνον 1.261; θυμοφθόρα φ. 2.329; so, after 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, προσανέα φ. 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 3.52; παιώνια 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 848; χρήσιμον 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 382c; θανάσιμα 3rd-2nd c.BC: Philo Mechanicus “(Belopoeica) Excerpte aus Philons Mechanik - Ath. Berl. Akad.” 103.31; ὀλέθριον 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Herm.” 62. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>healing remedy, medicine,</b> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] mostly of those applied outwardly, ἐπιθήσει φάρμαχ᾽ ἅ κεν παύσῃσι μελαινάων ὀδυνάων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.191 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπ᾽ ἄρ᾽ ἤπια φάρμακα πάσσε[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 218; ὀδυνήφατα φ. πάσσων 5.401, 900, compare 11.515, 830, 15.394; προσάλειφεν ἑκάστῳ φ. 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.392; φ. περιαλείφειν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 906 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also of potions, πιὼν φάρμακ᾽ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.326; φ. πεπωκώς 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.160, compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus [same place]; παρὰ τοῦ ἰατροῦ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 406d, compare “Grg.” 467c; φ. χριστόν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 516; ἔγχριστον 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 11.1; ἐπίχριστον 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 17.1.10; ἐπίπαστον 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus [same place]; καταπλαστόν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 716; ποτόν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hipp.” [same place]; frequently in in Medicine texts writers, 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 1.4, 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 6.265, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of <b>medicines</b> for cattle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PFlor.” 222.11 (3rd c.AD). \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__2.b</b></Level4> with <i>genitive</i> (see. below [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11), φ. νόσου \">Refs</a>]<b>a medicine for</b> it, <b>remedy against</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 251, 606 (Lyric poetry); βηχός 5th c.BC: Phrynichus Comicus 60: κεφαλῆς for a head-ache, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Charmides” 155b; στραγγουρίας 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 612b16, compare 624a16; μέθης 4th c.BC: Amphis Comicus 37; δίψης “Anthologia Graeca” 6.170 (1st c.BC: Thyillus Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but ὑγιείας φ. <b>a medicine to restore</b> or <b>maintain</b> health, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Aristides Rhetor “Orationes” 37(2).11. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <b>enchanted potion, philtre</b>: hence, <b>charm, spell,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.220f, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 302, 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 2.15, “PSI” 1.64.20 (1st c.BC)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φαρμάκοις τὸν ἄνδρ᾽ ἔμηνεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 561 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοιαῦτα ἔχω φ. such <b>charms</b> have I, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.85, cf. NT.Rev.9.21. \">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> <b>poison,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 685, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 385; πιεῖν τὸ φ. 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 6.15, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 57a, 115a; φάρμακα ἐσβεβληκέναι ἐς τὰ φρέατα 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.48; φ. δηλητήρια “SIG” 37 A 1 (Teos, 5th c.BC)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοξικὸν φ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “BGU” 21 ii 14 (4th c.AD). \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> <b>lye</b> for laundering, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Stud.Pal.” 22.56.12 (3rd c.AD). \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> generally, <b>remedy, cure,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 485, 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus 35, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; μεῖζον.. τῆς νόσου τὸ φ. <b>the cure</b> too strong for, i. e. worse than, the disease, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 589.4, compare “Comica Adespota” 455\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φ. πραΰ, of a bridle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 13.85; φ. τινι for a thing, 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 1134 (_plural_), 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 9; πρός τι 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1321a16; ποττὸν ἔρωτα 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 11.1 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; but most frequently φ. τινός <b>remedy against</b>.. χλαῖνα.. φ. ῥίγευς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Hipponax Iambographus 19; Ζεὺς πάντων φ. μοῦνος ἔχει 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 87; τὸ σιγᾶν φ. βλάβης ἔχω 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 548 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; φ. πόνων, λύπης, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 283, “fragment” 1079 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δόλοι.. χρείας ἀνάνδρου φ.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 288; φόβου 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 647e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; λήθης φάρμακα (of γράμματα) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 578.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; see at {εὐδιανός}. <br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> with <i>genitive</i> also, <b>a means of producing</b> something, φ. σωτηρίας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ph.” 893; μνήμης καὶ σοφίας φ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 274e; ὑπομνήσεως [prev. work] 275a, compare 230d; ἀθανασίας 4th c.BC: Antiphanes Comicus 86.6; ἡσυχίας 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1273b23 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φ. μανίας, of the oil applied to wrestlers, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD(?): Diogenes Laertius 1.104. \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> ἐπὶ θανάτῳ φ. ἑᾶς ἀρετᾶς εὑρέσθαι <b>a remedy</b> or <b>consolation in</b> his own virtue, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.187. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>dye, paint, colour,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 23.3, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.98, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 134, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 735, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 420c, “Plt.” 277c, “PCair.Zen.” 789.13 (3rd c.BC), etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>chemical reagent,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" PLeid.X. 25, “PHolm.” 13.46, 22.10, 2nd c.AD: Pseudo-Democritus Alchemista cited in Zos.Alch. p.160 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>used by tanners,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"Scholia 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 44, 368 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>].—Cf. φαρμάσσω. [μ; but μᾱ in φαρμακός.]","strongNumber":"G9619","accentedUnicode":"φάρμακον","shortDef":"a potion","mediumDef":"a potion","stepGloss":"a potion","stepTransliteration":"farmakon","_step_Type":"word"}]}